<H1>Richard Crashaw <span class="poet_dates">c.1612-1649</span></H1>

<p>Richard Crashaw was the son of a staunch Puritan preacher. He was educated at Pembroke College, Cambridge from where he
graduated in 1634 going on to become a fellow of Peterhouse.<P>

After the English Civil War he became a Roman Catholic and left England for France. Introduced to the French Queen,
Henrietta Maria, by his friend Abraham Cowley, another <NOBR>ex-Cambridge</NOBR> fellow who was working as her secretary, he was helped by her to obtain a position at Loreto Cathedral in Italy, where he
died in 1649.<P>

Crashaw's principal poetic work was the <i>Steps to the Temple</i>, a collection of religious poems published in
1646. Attached to this was a non-religious section entitled <i>Delights of the Muses</i>, which contains his best-known poem
<i>Wishes to his Supposed Mistress</i>. After his death his friend, Miles Pinkney, published a more complete volume of his works,
<i>Carmen Deo Nostro</i>.<P>

